PARAGRAPH.#text: Studying is a serious business. MetLife CEO Robert Henrikson reminisced at a New York conference last week about one university experience: "At the Wharton School, when they asked me how I became CEO, I said, 'Well, I was the oldest person at the company.' None of them laughed, and some of them wrote it down."Carl Icahn: private enemy No. 1? Since the veteran investor joined Seneca Capital in a shareholder rebellion to force Blackstone Group to up its offer for Dynegy, private-equity types muttered about the implications. It isn't the first time buyout barons have faced such a situation—remember Clear Channel Communications at the height on the boom? But they fear it will embolden investors again to push for more next time they buy a public company. And given the power company postponed the shareholder vote until this week, there is still potential for a bigger shock.

Headlines.Author: Frank Barnako
Headlines.Headline: Cautious outlook for 1998

#text:
Don't expect mutual funds to gain another 20 percent in net asset value
    next year. That's the "conventional wisdom" being heard from analysts looking
    ahead 12 months. One money manager on PBS's Wall Street Week television program last
    Friday night estimated that because of expected slower profit growth for corporations,
    stocks on average might rise seven to eight percent. The simple fact is the past three
    years have been historic, with the Standard
    & Poor's 500 index

rising each year more than 20 percent. Chicago-based investment
    research firm Ibbotson Associates says it's never done before.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Cautious outlook for 1998

Headlines.Author: Brenon Daly
Headlines.Headline: Oracle shares plunge 29%

#text:
Leading technology
    stocks lower, shares of Oracle

dropped 29 percent Tuesday on record-breaking volume after the world's largest maker of
    database software fell short of Wall Street's fiscal second-quarter earnings target, hurt
    by adverse currency-exchange rates. Lehman Bros., Morgan Stanley and Goldman, Sachs all
    cut their ratings on the news. The Redwood City, Calif.-based company said it earned 19
    cents per share, 4 cents less than the consensus estimate on Wall Street. Revenue
    increased 23 percent to $1.6 billion, but licensing fees rose only 3 percent. Oracle said
    revenue would have increased 29 percent if it weren't for the currency impact. The strong
    U.S. dollar -- currently trading around a 5 1/2-year high against the Japanese yen --
    makes Oracle's products and services more expensive in foreign countries. The company also
    blamed weak domestic sales to telecommunications companies. Oracle shares fell 9 7/16 to
    22 15/16, with 171 million shares changing hands on the Nasdaq exchange -- the biggest
    single-session volume in market history. Put another way, trades of Oracle shares
    represented part of one out of every four Nasdaq transactions.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Oracle shares plunge 29%

Headlines.Author: Mary Kennedy
Headlines.Headline: Grain mixed after export report

#text:
CHICAGO (CBS.MW) -- Grain pits at the Chicago Board of
    Trade settled mixed Friday in a shortened session for the Thanksgiving holiday weekend.
     Despite a lower close, January soybeansrose early
    amid bullish export sales for the week ended Nov. 20. Early Friday, the U.S.
    Department of Agriculture reported soybean sales at 705,700 metric tons, 25 percent higher
    than last week.
     December corn fell 0.6 percent as export sales were below traders'
    expectations. The USDA reported corn sales at 415,000 metric tons, 65 percent below the
    previous week. Wheat sales were 86 percent higher than last week at 728,900 metric tons.
     January soybeans fell 3 cents to $7.182 per bushel

December
    corn fell 1.6 cents to $2.806 per bushel and December wheat rose 1.6 cents to $3.576
    per bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade.
    
  
  
    
     Livestock markets at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
    were close to unchanged in quiet trading as many market players extended their holiday.
    The pork complex was basically steady as cash hogs were higher and the product was in
    better shape than it has been for the last several weeks. However, large kills are
    expected next week which prevented a rally. February
    live hogs

fell 0.075 cent to 60.475 cents per pound and February
    pork bellies

fell 0.6 cent to 57.025 cents per pound. 
     Lower cash prices and plentiful supplies weighed on cattle markets.
    Cash cattle trades were primarily 67 cents. Analysts said ifthe market doesn't see
    68 cents trades soon, look for the December contract to show weakness ahead of expiration.
     Feeder cattle was supported by weakness in the corn market. December
    live cattle

fell 0.1 cent to 67.20 cents per pound and March
    feeder cattle

rose 0.05 cent to 79.875 cents per pound. 
    
  
  
    
     All New York futures markets were closed for the
    extended Thanksgiving holiday.
     An announcement from ministers of the Organization of Petroleum
    Exporting Countries that they will indeed raise the production quota will pressure energy
    futures next week. OPEC has yet to settle on the production ceiling, currently set at 25
    million barrels per day.
